  "dataset": [
    {
      "@type": "Dataset",
      "@id": "https://robolawyer-tm.github.io/#dataset-claude_code_sessions",
      "name": "claude_code_sessions",
      "description": "I refuse to let my work evaporate when the terminal closes.\n\n- Every session becomes a durable artifact I can resume, replay, and mine later.\n- I keep two copies: a bit-faithful recording and a readable twin for human eyes.\n- Capture happens in the moment, because reconstruction from memory always loses something.\n- Continuous flushing means even a crash leaves me most of what happened.\n- What I build in an afternoon should still speak to me in a year.\n\nSilent failure frightens me more than loud failure ever could.\n\n- A trailing newline can corrupt a key while every local test passes.\n- Stale bookkeeping masquerades as missing data and wedges progress permanently.\n- Copying files to the wrong filesystem strips what makes them runnable, without a word.\n- I demand that transport faults halt loudly rather than record themselves as answers.\n- The defect that hides inside a passing roundtrip is the one that ruins me.\n\nEverything I make stays on my machine unless I consciously push it out.\n\n- Forgetting to configure something should protect me, never expose me.\n- Plaintext gets sealed before it travels; only ciphertext persists beyond my walls.\n- I distinguish raw private material from derived characterizations that carry different stakes.\n- Disclosure is an explicit act I perform, not a default I forgot to disable.\n\nI name my own things, in my own words, on purpose.\n\n- Inherited vocabulary drags in meanings I never chose; I reject the contamination.\n- A name should be readable at a glance and unmistakable in a directory listing.\n- Choosing a familiar word over a clever coinage is itself a deliberate act.\n- What I call things declares who owns the concepts underneath them.\n\nI move fast now and leave myself an honest map for later.\n\n- A rough end-to-end chain teaches me more than a polished fragment.\n- I spend scarce quota and money only where the real bottleneck lives.\n- Deferred refinements get named and parked, not silently abandoned.\n- The gap between what I wrote and what actually runs must eventually close.\n- Structure comes first; the files know where they belong before any code touches them.",
